er diary, Elizabeth was laying the foundation for the wider social vision to be found in her novels. Both works have been carefully edited and annotated from their original manuscripts by J A V Chapple and are accompanied by an illuminating introduction by Anita Wilson.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aParentingzEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomen novelists, Englishy19th centuryvDiaries. 0aWomenzEnglandvDiaries. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Letters.2bisacsh1 aWilson, Anita, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWilson, Anita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107804750 cprintz978185331070640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474465687423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474465687/original  a978-3-11-078047-5  Edinburgh University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK